result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: 15CM-398 and 15CM-489 - Both Cases Called @ 2:29 PM: Defendant Diana J. Kramarczyk in court with attorney David C. Rashid.  Scott C. Blader appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Global resolution has been reached and recited by DA.  Def and counsel concur with State's recital.    Defendant advised of minimum/maximum penalty.  Plea QN reviewed w/Defendant.  No impairment on proceeding today.  Plea colloquy entertained.  Collateral consequences explained. Chapter 950 compliance addressed.  Plea Ct 1:  NC  Plea Ct 3 POP:  NC  Court accepts plea and enters JOC.  Ct 2 DRI and 15CM-489 also DRI.   Argument by DA Blader.  Argument by Atty Rashid for lesser probation term with early termination. Statement by Def:  Yes.  The Court:  S/W - 18 mos probation.  Conditions: May petition for early term at any time after completion of 1 yr if joined by agent; No contact with the victim unless as required in a Court proceeding; the defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars where others are drinking and alcohol is being served, being in the restaurant or dining portion would not be considered a violation - must be in a separate dining area of the bar; and is prohibited from possessing/ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician; Not to be in the possession of any firearms unless authorized by supervising agent for the purpose of hunting and for which Def has DNR approval for that hunting season.  State provides NCIC information from a Winnebago Co 1981 Felony Conviction as to Diana Joyce Adams. Court reviews same and advises Def that she cannot possess any firearms due to that conviction.  She is advised to defer to counsel on any weapon possession.  Strict weapon prohibition due to conviction. Court Costs with DNA Sample and Surcharge ordered by the Court.  Defendant advised of right to expunge DNA record through the Department of Justice.  Court Appt Atty Fees imposed as a Court Costs.  By law forfeiture and destruction order as to 45 Cal Ruger - semi auto P90.  Apeal Rights Given.    No ID ordered as to 15CM-489.
